# Conventions

Code-quality rules the agent must follow on every task. Auto-loaded each session by `context-loader`. Referenced by `/bencium-next` Phase A (PLAN) and called out if a planned change would violate them.

Keep this file short. If a rule needs a paragraph of justification, link to a decision in `.harness/archive/` instead.

## File & component size

- **Per-file LOC cap: 800** for React/TS. Refactor before extending a file past **500**.
- One responsibility per component. Extract a sub-component when a component has more than 3 props of similar shape, or when a render branch is >80 lines.
- No monolith HTML/CSS files. Split by feature, not by file type.

## Stack defaults (override per project below)

- **UI primitives**: prefer shadcn/ui over hand-rolled. If shadcn doesn't have it, build it as a reusable component (not inline).
- **Styling**: Tailwind utility classes. No global CSS except resets and design tokens. No CSS-in-JS unless the project already uses it.
- **State**: local component state by default. Lift only when shared. No global store unless three+ unrelated components need the same data.
- **Routing**: framework-native (Next.js App Router, Astro routing). No custom router.

## LSP (read diagnostics before editing)

For any typed language with a language server, read the LSP diagnostics for the file before editing it. Don't ship code the LSP already flagged. This is a **pre-edit** check, not a post-edit check — catching a type error before you write the next line costs nothing; catching it after a 200-line refactor is expensive.

- **TypeScript / JavaScript:** tsserver / ts diagnostics — type errors, unused imports, unreachable code.
- **Python:** pyright + ruff — type errors, import issues, style violations that will fail CI.
- **Go:** gopls — type errors, unused imports, vet warnings.
- **Rust:** rust-analyzer — type errors, lifetime issues, unused warnings.

Skip silently for untyped contexts (bash, plain markdown, config files). A clean LSP at edit time prevents most of the "agent wrote code that doesn't compile" failure mode and is far cheaper than a retro after a failed verify.

## Ordering invariants

Some pairs of actions have a required order. Getting it wrong doesn't always produce a loud error — sometimes the second step silently breaks because the first step hasn't run. The harness encodes a few of these by default; your project may have its own.

**Encoded by the harness:**

- **PLAN → BUILD**: `/bencium-next` Phase B refuses to enter without explicit approval of Phase A.
- **RED → GREEN**: BUILD refuses to edit implementation files until the declared failing test is observed in red.
- **VERIFY (local) → DEPLOY**: `/bencium-deploy` refuses to run if `/bencium-verify` has any FAIL.
- **DEPLOY → SMOKE**: `[deployed]`-tagged ACCEPTANCE rows are never evaluated locally; only `/bencium-deploy` Step 5.5 may flip them.

**Pattern for your own invariants:** if a project step *must* run before another (database provisioned before secret request, auth before any user-route, migration before seed, lint before build), declare it in `.harness/rules.md` under the "Ordering invariants" subsection. The agent reads `rules.md` every session and will refuse to do step Y without step X — same enforcement model as the harness's own invariants.

Document the **why** on each invariant, not just the order. "Migration before seed (seed scripts assume the schema exists)" is enforceable; "migration before seed" alone forces the agent to guess the reason and may permit clever-but-wrong shortcuts.

## Token-cost discipline

- No inline base64 in source. Static assets go to `public/` or object storage.
- No copy-pasted sections. If a block appears twice, extract on the second occurrence; if three times, extract immediately.
- No unbounded prop drilling — if a prop traverses 3+ levels untouched, lift to context or restructure.
- No SELECT * in queries; specify columns. No blobs in list/poll endpoints.
- LLM calls: Haiku-first, conservative `max_tokens`, `cache_control` on stable prefixes.

## UI disclosure (always show what's happening)

The UI is the user's only window into the API, backend, and console. It must never hide work. Every async action must surface its state.

- **Loading**: any fetch/mutation/upload over ~150ms shows a visible loading indicator scoped to the affected element (button → spinner, list → skeleton, page → progress bar). No bare clicks that just "feel dead."
- **Progress**: long-running work (uploads, multi-step jobs, streaming LLM calls) shows real progress — bytes uploaded, current step, tokens streamed. A static "Loading..." for >3s is a bug.
- **Backend errors**: every failed request renders a user-visible error message with at minimum the HTTP status / error code and a "Retry" or next-step affordance. No silent failures, no errors that only appear in the browser console.
- **Console as last resort**: nothing important goes only to `console.log` / `console.error`. Console is for debugging; UI is for users. If it matters, it shows in the UI.
- **Disclosure for AI features**: model name, streaming state, token count (when known), and stop/retry controls visible. Users must know when they are talking to an LLM, which one, and that it's still working.

This is verified by the `UI discloses backend activity` row in `ACCEPTANCE.md` quality checks.

## TDD discipline (red → green)

- Every non-trivial task starts with a **failing test** that captures the "Done when" of the plan. Write the test, run it, observe red, *then* write the implementation.
- The plan in `/bencium-next` Phase A must name the test file and the assertion. Phase B refuses to edit implementation files until red is observed.
- Trivial tasks (typo, single-line rename, copy-only) may declare `Failing test: none — trivial (declared)`. Any other bypass requires an explicit `skip tdd` and a justification logged to `.harness/memory.md ## TDD bypasses`.
- A task is not done until the test passes locally **and** any related `[deployed]` ACCEPTANCE row passes against the live URL after `/bencium-deploy`.

## Quality gates

- Bilingual EN/HU preserved if applicable (keep á é í ó ö ő ú ü ű).
- Pagination on every list endpoint, default limit 25.
- No secrets in repo — env vars + .gitignore.
- New UI: invoke `bencium-innovative-ux-designer` or `impeccable` before coding; `design-review` after.
- New copy: invoke `typography` skill for correct quotes, dashes, spacing.
- **Pipelines verified end-to-end on both local and deployed env.** Never trust local-only success for any feature that touches the network, env vars, build pipeline, or runtime — re-verify on the live URL via `/bencium-deploy` SMOKE before marking shipped.

